\begin_layout Subsection*
What is Proprietary Software?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any software which does not disclose its source code under a permissive
 license is considered proprietary software.
 Some examples are Google, Google Chrome, Facebook, Photoshop, Microsoft
 Windows, and macOS.
 Proprietary software is usually sold for profit, or released as a free
 (as in money) service in exchange for user information.
 Whilst there is a wealth of ethically developed proprietary software, many
 of the most commonly known software companies are exteremely exploitative
 and take advantage of their users.
 There are many dangers to this kind of proprietary software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Cost of Proprietary Software
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the easily-reproducible nature of software, software companies which
 create unique products are easily able to create a monopoly.
 From many user's perspectives, there is only one search engine, only one
 image editor, and only a small handful of social media networks and operating
 systems.
 This is excellent for the pockets of technology company executives, but
 not good for consumers and entrepreneurs.
 As is to be expected with a monopoly or oligarchy, companies can jack up
 the prices for their software to whatever they wish, and consumers can
 do very little about it.
 In the case of Microsoft Windows, very few users know of any alternatives
 other than macOS, so Microsoft can do whatever they want to their customers.
 Recently, Microsoft started adding targeted advertisements to the Start
 Menu of their already costly operating system, and now have irremovable
 snooping tools that send Microsoft details about everything from your computer
 hardware to the amount of photos you have viewed in their 'Photos' application
 in the past day.
 In one report, the smallest possible amount of separate messages you can
 configure Windows to send to Microsoft is in the 5000s.
 Also, you can no longer disable forced updates, so you are totally at the
 mercy of whatever Microsoft throws at you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As well as Windows, the various services Google offers spy on users to an
 unacceptable degree.
 Google stores every search you ever make, the link to every website you
 ever visit in Google Chrome, and in other browsers, analytics from millions
 of websites.
 Google Analytics, a 'free' service that measures various statistics such
 as page views and location heatmaps, has its code embedded in millions
 of major websites, meaning that even without a Google account, using a
 browser other than Google Chrome, Google can still generate a comprehensive
 list of websites you visit and create targeted advertisements based on
 them.
 Google has even taken it to the next level, and created entire operating
 systems, (ChromeOS, Android and the unfinished mess Fuschia) that have
 spyware integrated into the operating systems themselves.
 Don't be mistaken - Google is an advertising company, not a search engine,
 not a cloud service provider, not an operating system development firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some software, like Photoshop, isn't renowned for spying or targeted advertising
, but rather comes with a massive up-front cost.
 Adobe Photoshop and Microsoft's Visual Studio (code editor) each cost upwards
 of $1000 per year for a license.
 This locks out a massive market of users in the third world who can't afford
