\begin_layout Section*
What is Open Source Software?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open Source means that the source code of a software package is publicly
 available and free for anyone to use.
 Some well known examples of open source software include Firefox, Linux,
 and MediaWiki, the software that powers Wikipedia.
 There are two main types of open source software.
 Some open source software is proprietary, meaning you must obtain a license
 to use it commercially.
 This type of software is not considered to be 'open source' by many, as
 the source code is not truly open for anyone to use as they wish.
 Usually, when people talk about open source software, they are talking
 about Free and Open Source Software (abbreviated as FOSS.) Note that the
 terms "Free software", "FOSS" and "Open Source Software" are used interchangeab
ly.
 Free software is free as in freedom, not just free as in price.
 In order to be classed as truly free software, a software package must
 follow the four freedoms, listed below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Four Freedoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• The freedom to run the program as you wish, for any purpose.
 • The freedom to study how the program works, and change it so it does
 your computing as you wish.
 Access to the source code is a precondition for this.
 • The freedom to redistribute copies so you can help your neighbour.
 • The freedom to distribute copies of your modified versions to others.
 By doing this you can give the whole community a chance to benefit from
 your changes.
 Access to the source code is a precondition for this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why Use Open Source Software?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open source software is essential as it respects the user.
 Because anyone can view the source code, anyone can audit free software
 to ensure that proper security measures are taken and that no malicious
 code is present, and many free software advocates do.
 The GNU/Linux and BSD operating systems are used extensively by many major
 technology companies for their servers, as they are extremely fast and
 secure.
 Because many more people view the source code than in proprietary software
 settings, bugs and security flaws are found much more quickly, and often
 patched within hours.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open source software is often much faster and supports many more platforms
 than proprietary software.
 Because anybody can contribute to free software projects, anyone can optimise
 and improve software to make it run on older hardware, or even different
 operating systems.
 Porting software to another operating system often requires minimal effort,
 and anyone who wishes to extend support for free software to their platform
 can easily do so; where they otherwise might have to open a support ticket
 for proprietary software and get a response along the lines of their feature
 request being denied due to lack of interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open source software does not spy on you.
 With the rise of advertising companies like Google, privacy can be a massive
 concern.
 Google's Chrome browser sends browsing history and usage statistics to
 Google, and uses that data for targeted advertising.
 Not only is this exploiting users, but if the security of a firm like Google
 were compromised, everyone's data would be compromised too.
 Additionally, because data-aggregation firms do not release the source
 code or even details of their security mechanisms, you can never be sure
 who to trust.
 Over 5 billion online accounts are known to have been compromised because
 of poor security practices in proprietary software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Free software is free.
 While companies like Adobe charge approximately $1000 a year for Photoshop,
 free software projects like Krita and the GNU Image Manipulation Program
 (GIMP) are completely free.
 It is extremely expensive for students and educational institutions to
 pay for software licensing, and free software can save people all over
 the world thousands of dollars.
 There is a massive variety of free software alternatives which are as good,
 or often better than their proprietary alternatives.
 Some other great examples of free software alternatives are Blender, a
 FOSS 3D modeller, Audacity, a FOSS audio editor, Krita, a FOSS image editor
 and painting tool, and KDenLive, a FOSS video editor on par with iMovie.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
On "Software Communism"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bill Gates is known to pass the Free Software movement as 'software communism.'
 This term perfectly describes the free software movement.
 There is one slight difference between the world of software and the 'real'
 world.
 Unlike the real world, software takes almost no effort to reproduce; once
 you have written the source code for a piece of software (the blueprint,)
 infinite versions of the software can be copied and distributed worldwide.
 This means that so called 'software communism' is actually possible, as
 there is an infinite supply of resources.
 However, proprietary software companies take advantage of their customers
 by charging high prices despite the infinite supply of program copies.
 By creating free software to compete with their proprietary equivalents,
 we can bring down the prices and force companies performing unethical spying
 to desist at the risk of losing their customers.
 By using free software, we are not only encouraging proprietary software
 companies to behave ethically, we are also getting high quality community
 built software for free!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Skeptical?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do people create free software? Many reasons.
 Many programmers, myself included, enjoy programming.
 Some people write and maintain free software projects for professional
 reasons.
 Some people write free software because they are sick of the inadequacies
 of proprietary software.
 Some write free software to give back to the community.
 A great article on the motives of writing free software is available on
 the Free Software Foundation's website at https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/fs-motiv
es.html
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does software developed without funding become as useful as commercialised
 software? Many people are sponsored or paid full time to write free software
 by corporations in need of better software.
 Some, like the maintainers of the Linux Mint operating system, receive
 enough donations to live off.
 Many people who are skeptical of open source software don't recognise the
 generosity of many people.
 Even if only 1 in 10 000 people writes free software as a hobby, that's
 70 000 people.
 The amount of people who are able to benefit from free software is massive,
 and often corporations will sponsor free software projects that they depend
 on for their products and services to function.
 There are multiple entire families of operating systems that are entirely[1]
 free and open source.
 Ubuntu GNU/Linux, Linux Mint, Fedora, openSUSE, Arch Linux, Gentoo GNU/Linux,
 FreeBSD, OpenBSD and hundreds of other derivatives are all built by the
 free software community.
 If you doubt their security, consider OpenBSD, which has had 2 security
 vulnerabilities in its decades long history.
 Firefox, a fully featured FOSS browser, is built by the non-profit organisation
 Mozilla, and is better than Chrome in every way[2].
\end_layout

